{{Infobox religious biography |background = #FFD068 | color = black |name = Nányuè Huáiràng |image = |caption = |birth name = |alias = |dharma name = |birth_date = 677 |birth_place = [[Jinzhou]], [[China]] |death_date = 744 |death_place = |nationality = [[Chinese people|Chinese]] |religion = [[Ch'an]] |school = |lineage = |title = [[Ch'an master]] |location = |education = |occupation = |teacher = [[Dajian Huineng]] |reincarnation of = |predecessor = |successor = [[Mazu Daoyi]] |students = |spouse = |partner = |children = |website = }} '''Nányuè Huáiràng''' (南嶽懐譲, [[Japanese language|Japanese]]: Nangaku Ejõ) (677–744)<ref name="ferguson">{{cite book|last=Ferguson|first=Andrew|title=Zen's Chinese Heritage: The Masters and Their Teachings|page=53|year=2011|publisher=Wisdom Publications|url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=978-0861716173|isbn=978-0861716173}}</ref> was the foremost student of [[Dajian Huineng]],<ref name="ferguson"/> the 6th Patriarch of [[Ch'an]] ([[Zen]]) and teacher of one of his [[Dharma heir]]s, [[Mazu Daoyi]].<ref name="ferguson"/>
== Life == The ancestor of two of the [[Five Houses of Chán|Five Houses]] of Ch'an, Huairang is traditionally said to have studied with a [[Vinaya]] master and became ordained. Dissatisfied with his own progress, Huairang found [[Dajian Huineng]] in [[Shaozhou]] and became his disciple, which is recorded in various traditional biographies. Huairang is traditionally said to have given Dharma transmission to six individuals, the most prominent being [[Mazu Daoyi]].<ref>{{cite book| last =Faure| first =Bernard| authorlink =| coauthors =| title =The Rhetoric of Immediacy: A Cultural Critique of Chan/Zen Buddhism| publisher =Princeton University Press| year =1991| location =| pages =12| url =http://www.worldcat.org/search?qt=worldcat_org_all&q=0691029636| doi =| id = | isbn = 0-691-02963-6}}</ref>
Based on a critical reading of the textual evidence, the scholar John McRae notes that it is unlikely that Huairang actually practiced with Huineng. In the oldest version of the ''[[Platform Sutra]]'' found among the [[Dunhuang manuscripts]], which dates to about 850 CE, Nanyue is not listed as a student of Huineng at all. Although Huairang is mentioned in 952 CE in the ''[[Anthology of the Patriarchal Hall]]'', he is not discussed in the context of Huineng. The same source records a putative coversation between him and Mazu, but there is no explicit suggestion that Mazu is his student. An even earlier source, the ''Transmissions of the Treasure Grove'' of 801, states that Huairang was enlightened under Lao'an, a teacher with connections to [[Shenxiu]] of the so-called Northern School.<ref name=McRae>{{citation|last=McRae|first=John|title=Seeing Through Zen|year=2003|publisher=University of California Press||page=80-82|location=Berkeley, Los Angeles, London|isbn=978-0-520-23798-8}}</ref>
