{{Infobox Book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Thought and Action | image = File:Thought and Action.JPG | image_caption = Cover of the first edition | author = [[Stuart Hampshire]] | country = United Kingdom | language = English | subject = [[Action theory (philosophy)|Action theory]] | publisher = [[Chatto and Windus]] | pub_date = 1959 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]]) | pages = 276 | isbn = 978-0268018474 }} '''''Thought and Action''''' is a 1959 book by the philosopher [[Stuart Hampshire]].<ref name="Downie">[[#Dow05|Downie 2005]]. p. 358.</ref> The book has received praise from commentators, and is considered Hampshire's major work.<ref name="Downie" />
==Summary== Hampshire develops in greater detail ideas about freedom and the [[philosophy of mind]] that he had already explored in his ''[[Spinoza (book)|Spinoza]]'' (1951). He examines a set of contrasts between that which is unavoidable in human thought and that which is contingent, between knowledge and decision, criticism and practice, philosophy and experience.<ref name="Downie" /> He argues that [[Empiricism|empiricist]] theories of perception descending from [[George Berkeley]] and [[David Hume]] mistakenly represent people as passive observers receiving impressions from "outside" of the mind, where the "outside" includes their own bodies.<ref>[[#Ham59|Hampshire 1959]]. p. 47.</ref>
==Reception== The historian [[Peter Gay]] wrote that ''Thought and Action'' is a "brilliant" and "lucid" contribution to the philosophy of action, and a subtle vindication of [[free will]].<ref>[[#Gay76|Gay 1976]]. p. 237.</ref> The philosopher [[Roger Scruton]], writing in ''[[Sexual Desire (book)|Sexual Desire]]'' (1986), credited Hampshire with providing a seminal discussion of two contrasting outlooks on the future that can be called "predicting and deciding."<ref>[[#Scr94|Scruton 1994]]. p. 333.</ref> The philosopher [[Anthony Quinton, Baron Quinton|Anthony Quinton]] wrote that Hampshire's "systematic aim and fine mandarin prose were both unusual for an Oxford philosopher of the time."<ref>[[#Qui05|Quinton 2005]]. p. 546.</ref>
