{{for|the agriculturalist|William Ormston Backhouse}}
'''William Backhouse''' (17 January, 1593 – 30 May, 1662) was a renowned [[England|English]] [[Rosicrucian]] [[philosopher]], [[Alchemy|alchemist]], and [[astrologer]]. He was born on 17 January 1593 at [[Swallowfield Park]], some 5 miles south of [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] in the county of [[Berkshire]], a younger son of [[Samuel Backhouse]]. He entered [[Christ Church, Oxford]], in 1610, but left the university without taking a degree.<ref name=berkhist>{{cite web | title = Berkshire History: Biographies: William Backhouse (1593-1662) | url = http://www.berkshirehistory.com/bios/wbackhouse.html | publisher = Nash Ford Publishing | year = 2002 | accessdate = 2007-08-29}}</ref><ref name=DNB>{{Cite DNB|wstitle=Backhouse, William}}</ref> He learned some mathematics from [[John Blagrave]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=John David North|author2=John James Roche|title=The Light of nature: essays in the history and philosophy of science presented to A. C. Crombie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PEJxzA6mSB0C&pg=PA266|accessdate=3 April 2012|year=1985|publisher=Springer Science & Business|isbn=978-90-247-3165-7|pages=268}}</ref>

Backhouse married Anne Richards, the daughter of Brian Richards of [[Hartley Wespall]] in [[Hampshire]], by whom he had two sons (who predeceased him), and a daughter, [[Flower Backhouse]]. Backhouse also adopted [[Elias Ashmole]], founder of the [[Ashmolean Museum]], as his son, encouraging him in his studies. Backhouse died at Swallowfield Park, on 30 May 1662.<ref name=berkhist /><ref name=DNB />

